We aim to study on data about electricity consumption in Turkey from the beginning of 2016 to May 20th, 2021. We analyze the time series and built an ARIMA model using suitable AR and MA models. Then, we will predict new consumption data and check the error.

Required libraries

library(ggplot2)
library(fpp)
library(data.table)
library(readxl)
library(forecast)
library(lubridate)
require(urca)

plot(acf(cons, lag.max = 24), main = " ACF Graph of Consumption Data with Lag = 24 ")

plot(pacf(cons, lag.max = 24), main = " PACF Graph of Consumption Data with Lag = 24 ")

Data is not stationary. There are autocorrelations.We will decompose data by hours, days, weeks… Starting with 24(days).

cons_day=ts(data$cons,freq=24)
decomp_day=decompose(cons_day, type="additive")
plot(decomp_day)

We couldn’t find a trend line. But the random seems stationary. Let’s try by 168(week).

cons_week=ts(data$cons,freq=168)
decomp_week=decompose(cons_week, type="additive")
plot(decomp_week)

We can see seasonality.Let’s look at yearly(52 weeks) frequency before we choose this data.

cons_year=ts(data$cons,freq=8736)
decomp_year=decompose(cons_year, type="additive")
plot(decomp_year)

An increasing trend is more visible in yearly frequency. Consumption decreased in pandemic period.

Let’s manipulate weekly decomposed data.

Trend=decomp_week$trend
Seasonal=decomp_week$seasonal
Random=decomp_week$random
stationaritytest=ur.kpss(Random)
summary(stationaritytest)
## 
## ####################### 
## # KPSS Unit Root Test # 
## ####################### 
## 
## Test is of type: mu with 18 lags. 
## 
## Value of test-statistic is: 0.0042 
## 
## Critical value for a significance level of: 
##                 10pct  5pct 2.5pct  1pct
## critical values 0.347 0.463  0.574 0.739

We have low test-statistic so, data is stationary. Now we check ACF and PACF.

acf(Random, lag.max = 168, na.action = na.pass,  main = " ACF for Weekly Data ")

pacf(Random, lag.max = 168, na.action = na.pass,  main = " PACF for Weekly Data")

ACF graph decreaswes exponentially. We can see a spike at lag 2. Try some Autoregressive models, priority p value is 2.

Second ARIMA model has a little less value. Let’s check residuals first and make forecasts with that. We can forecast for 420 step (84+14*24).

checkresiduals(arima2)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(5,0,5) with non-zero mean
## Q* = 232595, df = 325, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
## Model df: 11.   Total lags used: 336
fitted= Random - arima2$residuals
transformed_fitted = fitted + Trend + Seasonal
forecast = predict(arima2, n.ahead = 420)$pred
forecast_ts = ts(forecast, frequency = 168, start=c(279,85))
last=transformed_fitted[46500:47208]
plot(cons_week[46500:47208], type = "line", main = "Electricity Consumption between 01.01.2016 - 20.05.2021  (real data and prediction)", ylab = "MWh", xlab = "Hours")
points(last, col="blue")

tren = tail(Trend[!is.na(Trend)],1)
tail(Seasonal,1)
## Time Series:
## Start = c(281, 168) 
## End = c(281, 168) 
## Frequency = 168 
## [1] 1075.342
season = Seasonal[1:420]
forecas = forecast_ts + tren + season
plot(cons_week, type= "line", ylab = "MWh ", xlab = "Hours", main="Electricity Consumption between 01.01.2016 - 20.05.2021  (real data and prediction)", xlim=c(279,283))
points(forecas, col = "red")

Let’s calculate the errors.

real_data = cons[46873:47208]
error = real_data - forecas[85:420]
daily_error=0
daily_real=0

daily_error[1] = sum(error[1:24])
daily_real[1] = sum(real_data[1:24])


  for(i in 1:13){
  a=i*24
  daily_error[i] = sum(error[a:(a+24)])
  daily_real[i] = sum(real_data[a:(a+24)])
  i=i+1
  }
